<main id="main-content">
    <section class="hero pb-8">
      <div class="container">
        <h1 class="hero__title">Frequently asked questions</h1>
        <p class="hero__subtitle">AZERTY Global explained in English — installation, French accents, your language, going back.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section pt-0">
      <div class="container container--narrow">

        <!-- Installation & setup -->
        <h2 class="mb-4 mt-8">💾 Installation and setup</h2>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">How do I install AZERTY Global on Windows?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>The recommended option is the <strong>Microsoft Store app</strong>: no admin rights, automatic
              updates, built-in virtual keyboard and character search. If the Store is blocked (for example on a
              company computer), a <strong>signed MSIX</strong> package allows a direct installation. A classic
              <strong>EXE installer</strong> is also available for PCs without the Store.</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">→ <a href="/en/download">Go to the download page</a></p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Do I need admin rights to install it?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>No</strong>, not with the Microsoft Store app — it installs without admin rights and
              without any SmartScreen warning. Only the classic EXE installer requires admin rights.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Is AZERTY Global available on Mac and Linux?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>Yes!</strong> AZERTY Global is available on <strong>Windows</strong>, <strong>macOS</strong>
              (10.12+) and <strong>Linux</strong> (Ubuntu, Debian, Fedora, Arch...).</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">→ <a href="/en/download">Download for your platform</a></p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">How do I keep AZERTY Global as default after a restart?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <h3>Microsoft Store app</h3>
            <p>Right-click the AG icon in the taskbar → <strong>Launch at Windows startup</strong>.</p>

            <h3 class="mt-3">EXE installer</h3>
            <p>If Windows switches back to your old layout after a restart, remove the keyboard layouts you no
              longer need (<em>Settings → Time &amp; language → Language &amp; region → French (⋯) → Language
              options → Keyboards</em>), or set AZERTY Global as the default input method in
              <em>Settings → Typing → Advanced keyboard settings</em>.</p>

            <h3 class="mt-3">macOS and Linux</h3>
            <p>Once added, AZERTY Global stays available after a restart. Remove the layouts you no longer use
              so it remains the active one.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <!-- Compatibility -->
        <h2 class="mb-4 mt-8">🖥️ Compatibility</h2>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Does AZERTY Global work if my Windows is in English?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>Yes.</strong> A keyboard layout is independent from the display language of your system:
              you can use AZERTY Global on a Windows, macOS or Linux system set to English or any other language.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Does it work with video games (ZQSD)?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>Yes for ZQSD movement.</strong> The physical keys do not move, so your controls stay in
              place. The Microsoft Store app can pause itself on some anti-cheat protected games to avoid any
              ban risk.</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">→ Known cases and solutions on the <a href="/compatibilite">compatibility page (in French)</a></p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Will it work in all my applications?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>Yes.</strong> A keyboard layout works system-wide: browsers, office suites, code editors,
              chat apps... Everything that accepts text input uses your active layout.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <!-- What changes -->
        <h2 class="mb-4 mt-8">🔄 What changes vs the standard AZERTY</h2>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">What exactly changes?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Only <strong>5 things</strong> — and each one makes typing easier:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Smart Caps Lock</strong> — É, È, Ç, À in one key press</li>
              <li><strong>Direct period access</strong> — period and semicolon swapped</li>
              <li><strong>@ and # on the top-left key</strong>, where ² usually is</li>
              <li><strong>Programming symbols on the home row</strong> — { } [ ] | \ with AltGr</li>
              <li><strong>International accents on the ù key</strong> — acute ´, grave ` and tilde ~</li>
            </ul>
            <p>All the letters and numbers stay where they are: <strong>99% of your habits preserved</strong>.</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">→ <a href="/en/guide">Learn the 5 changes in 2 minutes</a></p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">How long does it take to adjust?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Most users are comfortable within <strong>a few hours</strong>. The 5 changes are quick to
              memorize; the reflexes settle in after a few days of use.</p>
            <p>Less than 1% of your keystrokes will be different! The letters and numbers do not move.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">What is a keyboard layout, anyway?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>When you press a key, your keyboard sends a key number to the computer, not a letter. The
              <strong>layout</strong> — a software setting of your system — decides which letter or symbol
              appears. "AZERTY" is simply the layout used in France, named after the first six letters of its
              top row.</p>
            <p>Because it is all software, it can be improved without changing your keyboard: AZERTY Global
              replaces your computer's AZERTY while keeping your letters and most symbols in place — only a few
              characters become easier to reach.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Do I need to buy a new keyboard or stickers?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>No.</strong> AZERTY Global is purely software: your current keyboard works perfectly.
              The letters (A-Z) and numbers do not move. Stickers can help during the first days but are not
              required — printable PDF files are included in the download.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <!-- Typing French -->
        <h2 class="mb-4 mt-8">🔤 Typing French</h2>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">How do I type É, È, À and Ç?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Turn <kbd>Caps Lock</kbd> on and press the <kbd>é</kbd>, <kbd>è</kbd>, <kbd>à</kbd> or
              <kbd>ç</kbd> key. With AZERTY Global, Caps Lock only affects letters — so it produces
              <strong>É, È, À, Ç</strong> in one key press instead of numbers.</p>
            <p>Capital accented letters are required in proper French ("État", "À bientôt", "Ça va") — schools
              and style guides agree on this.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">How do I type French quotation marks « » and the spaces that go with them?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><kbd>AltGr</kbd> + <kbd>W</kbd> for <strong>«</strong> and <kbd>AltGr</kbd> + <kbd>X</kbd> for
              <strong>»</strong>.</p>
            <p>French typography also uses a <strong>narrow non-breaking space</strong> before ? ! : ; and inside
              quotation marks: it is on <kbd>AltGr</kbd> + <kbd>Space</kbd> (regular non-breaking space:
              <kbd>AltGr</kbd> + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>Space</kbd>).</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">How do I type œ, æ and the dashes?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>œ</strong> (as in "cœur"): <kbd>AltGr</kbd> + <kbd>O</kbd> —
              <strong>æ</strong>: <kbd>AltGr</kbd> + <kbd>A</kbd>.</p>
            <p>En dash <strong>–</strong>: <kbd>AltGr</kbd> + <kbd>T</kbd> — em dash <strong>—</strong>:
              <kbd>AltGr</kbd> + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>T</kbd>.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <!-- Typing your native language -->
        <h2 class="mb-4 mt-8">🌍 Typing your own language</h2>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Which languages can I type with AZERTY Global?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>Well over one hundred Latin-script languages</strong>, including:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><span class="faq-language-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇪🇸</span> <strong>Spanish</strong>: ñ, ¿, ¡</li>
              <li><span class="faq-language-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇩🇪</span> <strong>German</strong>: ä, ö, ü, ß</li>
              <li><span class="faq-language-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇵🇹</span> <strong>Portuguese</strong>: ã, õ, ç</li>
              <li><span class="faq-language-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇮🇹</span> <strong>Italian</strong>: à, è, ì, ò, ù</li>
              <li><span class="faq-language-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇩🇰🇸🇪</span> <strong>Nordic languages</strong>: þ, ø, å</li>
              <li><span class="faq-language-flag" aria-hidden="true">🌍</span> <strong>African languages</strong>: over 75 characters for Wolof, Bambara, Yoruba, Hausa, Ewe and more (ɛ, ɔ, ŋ, ɲ…)</li>
              <li><span class="faq-language-flag" aria-hidden="true">🇵🇱🇨🇿🇭🇺🇷🇴🇹🇷</span> And many more...</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">How do dead keys work?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>A dead key types an accent first, then applies it to the next letter you press.
              Example: <kbd>´</kbd> then <kbd>A</kbd> → <strong>á</strong>.</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Acute ´</strong>: key right of <kbd>M</kbd> → á, í, ó, ú</li>
              <li><strong>Grave `</strong>: <kbd>Shift</kbd> + key right of <kbd>M</kbd> → ì, ò, ù</li>
              <li><strong>Tilde ~</strong>: <kbd>AltGr</kbd> + key right of <kbd>M</kbd> → ñ, ã, õ</li>
              <li><strong>Diaeresis ¨</strong> and <strong>circumflex ^</strong>: unchanged from the standard AZERTY → ä, ö, ü, â, ê…</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">→ Full list in the <a href="/en/guide">quick guide</a></p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <!-- Going back & general -->
        <h2 class="mb-4 mt-8">❓ Going back and general questions</h2>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">How do I switch back to the standard AZERTY?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>At any time — <strong>your original layout is never modified</strong>.</p>
            <h3>Microsoft Store app</h3>
            <p>Press <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>Caps Lock</kbd> to turn AZERTY Global off
              instantly, or right-click the AG tray icon. To remove it: <kbd>Win</kbd> + <kbd>I</kbd> →
              <strong>Apps</strong> → <strong>Installed apps</strong> → "AZERTY Global" → <strong>Uninstall</strong>.</p>
            <h3 class="mt-3">EXE installer</h3>
            <p>Press <kbd>Win</kbd> + <kbd>Space</kbd> to switch layouts, or remove AZERTY Global in
              <em>Settings → Time &amp; language → Language &amp; region → French (⋯) → Language options</em>.</p>
            <h3 class="mt-3">macOS and Linux</h3>
            <p>Select your previous layout again in your system settings and remove AZERTY Global from your
              input sources.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Is AZERTY Global free? Open source?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>Yes and yes.</strong> AZERTY Global is free and open source, licensed under
              <strong>EUPL 1.2</strong> (a European free software license). The source code is available on
              <a href="https://github.com/AZERTYGlobal" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a>.
              No account, no telemetry, no hidden cost.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Is it safe? What about my privacy?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>AZERTY Global <strong>never logs, stores or transmits your keystrokes</strong>. The Microsoft
              Store app has no telemetry, requires no account, and its usage statistics are 100% local to your
              device — nothing is ever transmitted.</p>
            <p>The whole project is open source: you (or your IT department) can audit it on
              <a href="https://github.com/AZERTYGlobal" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Who is behind AZERTY Global?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>AZERTY Global is created by <strong>Antoine Olivier</strong>, president of the
              <strong>AMCF</strong> (Association pour la Modernisation du Clavier Français), a French nonprofit
              association. The project has been developed as free software since 2017.</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">→ Questions or feedback? <a href="mailto:contact@azerty.global">contact@azerty.global</a> or <a href="https://discord.gg/nYknqshJz3" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Discord</a></p>
          </div>
        </details>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA -->
    <section class="final-cta">
      <div class="container">
        <h3 class="mb-4 text-2xl">Ready to try?</h3>
        <p class="mb-6 text-white">
          Download AZERTY Global and finally type É, œ and « » effortlessly.
        </p>
        <a href="/en/download" class="btn btn--lg text-white bg-black-30 backdrop-blur border-white-20">
          Download for free
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>
